> Noodle stir-fries are the ultimate one-bowl vegetarian comfort food! You'll toss
> tender, chewy noodles with snow peas, zucchini, and carrots in an umami-rich mix
> of soy sauce, sweet chili sauce, and fresh ginger, along with a splash of tangy
> rice wine vinegar. Finish with crispy fried onions and scallion greens for even
> more flavor and crunch.

Bring a large #pot{} of water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and halve @carrots{9%ounce} lengthwise; cut on a diagonal into 1/4-inch-thick pieces. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}. Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut on a diagonal into 1/4-inch-thick half-moons. Trim and remove strings from @snow peas{4%ounce}.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to #pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Reserve 1/2 cup noodle cooking water, then drain and set aside.

While noodles cook, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add carrots, scallion whites, and ginger; cook, stirring occasionally, until just starting to soften, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Increase heat to high. Add zucchini and snow peas to pan. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies are tender, ~{3-5%minutes} more.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, @Vidalia onion paste{1/2%ounce}, half the @rice wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, half the @soy sauce{2%tablespoon}, and 1/4 cup water.

Stir @garlic powder{1%teaspoon} into pan with veggies. Add drained noodles, chili-soy sauce, and 1 TBSP @butter{1%tablespoon}. Cook, tossing, until butter has melted and everything is coated and saucy, ~{30-60%seconds}.

> TIP: If needed, add reserved noodle cooking water a splash at a time until
> everything is thoroughly coated in sauce.

Taste and season with remaining soy sauce if desired.

Divide stir-fry between shallow #bowls{}; top with @crispy fried onions{1} and scallion greens. Serve.